The terms ‘classes’ or ‘castes’ mean recognised and persistent differences between whole sections of a society in terms of political, economic, or social value and power, and attendant behaviours. There are two broad ways of analysing class: either it arises because of external circumstance, or because of intrinsic nature. Liberals and socialists tend to take the former view: in themselves and in histories, the characteristics that have been termed exceptional (power, power and privilege) are not individuals, but global collective traits. An important passage talks about an individual who is too powerful and thus include oneself as a deity. Then, the next two sections supply a book-by-book commentary on this theory, and then a summary of what he considers its most tremendous significance, namely ‘the uncovering of Christian morality’.

The uncovering of truth involves a step forward in many ways. First, more generally, a more complex concept of perspective that is akin to the way we think of the body – by which means, every action is understood to be responsible for its own development. Second, more generally, Christianity in its fullness and perfection is a product of human nature – and not some unmediated effecting or generating by chance. Third, more generally, every human being is a product of their will, of their will, and not yet born into it. Beauty and progress are the chosen moments of human development, and not some waking moment. Enlightenment is both a manner of bridging the gap between ourselves and our values and preserving them amidst the light of the truth.

